243
00:20:25,020 --> 00:20:27,780
Don't he have the grandest
singin' voice?

244
00:20:27,860 --> 00:20:30,660
John, Pearl,
run along and play, you two.

245
00:20:30,740 --> 00:20:32,900
- Where?
- Down by the river. My goodness!

246
00:20:35,060 --> 00:20:37,620
That f ella's just achin' to settle down
with some nice woman...

247
00:20:37,740 --> 00:20:39,660
and make a home for himself.

248
00:20:39,780 --> 00:20:42,180
Icey, it's awful soon
after Ben's passing.

249
00:20:42,260 --> 00:20:46,540
- If ever I saw a sign from heaven.
- John don't like him much.

250
00:20:46,660 --> 00:20:49,820
- Pearl dotes on him.
- The boy worries me.

251
00:20:50,780 --> 00:20:54,380
I know it's silly, but it's like there's
something still between him and his dad.

252
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:56,940
What he needs
is a dose of sauce.

253
00:20:57,020 --> 00:20:59,700
- No, there's somethin' else.
- What?

254
00:20:59,820 --> 00:21:02,300
- The money.
- I declare, Willa Harper...

255
00:21:02,420 --> 00:21:05,020
you'll let that money haunt you
to your grave.

256
00:21:05,140 --> 00:21:07,020
Icey, I would
love to be satisfied...

257
00:21:07,140 --> 00:21:09,780
that Harry Powell don't think I got
that money hid somewhere.

258
00:21:09,900 --> 00:21:12,860
You come right out
and ask that man of God.

259
00:21:12,980 --> 00:21:16,900
Mr. Powell! Clear that evil mud
out of your soul.

260
00:21:16,980 --> 00:21:20,620
John! Pearl! Come along here,
get some fudge.

261
00:21:20,740 --> 00:21:23,140
- I don't want no fudge.
- You do what you're told!

262
00:21:23,260 --> 00:21:26,380
- You go sit down by the river.
- Oh, Icey, I'm a sight.

263
00:21:26,460 --> 00:21:28,340
Get along with you.

264
00:21:33,100 --> 00:21:34,420
You!

265
00:21:36,540 --> 00:21:39,180
That young lady better look sharp,
or some smart sister...

266
00:21:39,300 --> 00:21:41,780
is gonna snap him up
right from under her nose.

267
00:21:41,900 --> 00:21:43,860
She's not the only fish
in the river.

268
00:21:43,980 --> 00:21:47,060
Now, you two stay put.
Shilly-shallying around.

269
00:21:47,180 --> 00:21:49,340
A husband's one piece of store goods
you never know...

270
00:21:49,460 --> 00:21:51,500
till you get it home
and take the paper off.

271
00:21:51,620 --> 00:21:56,180
Did Ben Harper ever tell you
what he done with the money he stole?

272
00:21:56,300 --> 00:21:59,220
My dear child, don't you know?

273
00:22:00,460 --> 00:22:02,580
She's moanin' about Ben Harper.

274
00:22:02,700 --> 00:22:05,220
That wasn't love.
That was just flapdoodle.

275
00:22:05,300 --> 00:22:07,140
Have some fudge, lambs.

276
00:22:07,220 --> 00:22:09,100
When you've been married
to a man for 40 years...

277
00:22:09,180 --> 00:22:11,660
you know all that don't amount
to a hill of beans.

278
00:22:11,780 --> 00:22:15,420
I've been married to my Walt that long,
and I swear in all that time...

279
00:22:15,540 --> 00:22:18,460
I just lie there
thinkin' about my canning.

280
00:22:34,460 --> 00:22:37,740
A woman's a fool to marry for that.
That's somethin' for a man.

281
00:22:37,820 --> 00:22:40,500
The Good Lord never meant
for a decent woman to want that.

282
00:22:40,620 --> 00:22:42,660
Not really want it.

283
00:22:42,740 --> 00:22:45,460
It's all just a fake
and a pipe dream.

284
00:22:47,380 --> 00:22:50,060
John, Mr. Powell
has something to tell you.

285
00:22:52,740 --> 00:22:57,100
Well, John, the night before
your father died...

286
00:22:57,220 --> 00:23:00,540
he told me what he did
with that money.

287
00:23:00,660 --> 00:23:03,020
That money's
at the bottom of the river...

288
00:23:03,140 --> 00:23:06,460
wrapped around
a 12-pound cobblestone.

289
00:23:07,540 --> 00:23:09,100
Thank you, Harry.

290
00:23:10,700 --> 00:23:12,700
I f eel clean now.

291
00:23:12,820 --> 00:23:15,820
My whole body's
just a-quiverin' with cleanness.

292
00:23:20,460 --> 00:23:22,380
John, come here.

293
00:23:22,500 --> 00:23:24,500
Your tie is crooked.

294
00:23:38,420 --> 00:23:41,500
Along the river shore

295
00:23:41,620 --> 00:23:44,940
Birdie Steptoe was a pilot

296
00:23:45,060 --> 00:23:47,860
In the good ol' days of yore

297
00:23:47,980 --> 00:23:52,140
Now he sets in his ol' wharf boat

298
00:23:52,260 --> 00:23:54,860
All the big boats heave a sigh

299
00:23:54,980 --> 00:23:57,900
- When will Dad's skiff be ready?
- Can't hear you, boy.

300
00:23:58,020 --> 00:24:02,460
They blow for Uncle Birdie and

301
00:24:02,580 --> 00:24:06,860
The times that ere gone by

302
00:24:06,980 --> 00:24:08,820
When will the skiff be ready?

303
00:24:08,900 --> 00:24:11,820
Have her ready inside a week,
and then we'll go fishin'.

304
00:24:11,940 --> 00:24:15,220
- How's your ma?
- Oh, she's all right.

305
00:24:15,340 --> 00:24:17,340
- How's your sister Pearl?
- Just fine.

306
00:24:17,460 --> 00:24:20,340
- You leavin', boy?
- Yep. Gotta watch out for Pearl.

307
00:24:20,460 --> 00:24:23,140
Well, good night, boy.
Come again anytime.

308
00:24:24,180 --> 00:24:27,820
And mind, boy, I'll have your pa's skiff
shipshape inside a week.

309
00:24:56,460 --> 00:24:58,260
Is somebody there?

310
00:25:08,020 --> 00:25:09,860
Anybody there?

311
00:25:13,100 --> 00:25:14,900
Anybody here?

312
00:25:15,020 --> 00:25:17,020
Good evenin', John.

313
00:25:18,980 --> 00:25:21,780
I had a little talk
with your mother tonight, John...

314
00:25:21,900 --> 00:25:26,860
and your mother decided it might be best
for me to let you know the news.

315
00:25:26,980 --> 00:25:31,500
Your mother told me she wanted me
to be a daddy to you and your sister.

316
00:25:31,620 --> 00:25:33,580
We're gonna get married, boy.

317
00:25:35,300 --> 00:25:39,420
Did you hear what I said, boy?
Married.

318
00:25:40,180 --> 00:25:43,300
We're going to Sisterville tomorrow,
and when we get back--

319
00:25:43,380 --> 00:25:46,860
You ain't my dad.
You'll never be my dad.

320
00:25:46,940 --> 00:25:50,380
When we get back,
we're all going to be friends...

321
00:25:50,500 --> 00:25:53,220
and share our fortunes
together, John.

322
00:25:53,300 --> 00:25:56,540
You think you can make me tell,
but I won't, I won't, I won't!

323
00:25:59,540 --> 00:26:02,740
- Tell me what, boy?
- Nothin'.

324
00:26:02,860 --> 00:26:06,140
We're not keeping secrets
from each other, are we, little lad?

325
00:26:10,060 --> 00:26:14,620
Well, no matter.
We've got a long time together, boy.

326
00:26:21,300 --> 00:26:24,420
Raise your hand! Great sakes!

327
00:26:24,500 --> 00:26:27,300
Now you wait here
while I get your night things.

328
00:26:32,300 --> 00:26:34,740
- Now can I tell?
- Hmm?

329
00:26:34,860 --> 00:26:37,940
Mr. Powell's our daddy now.
Can I tell him about--

330
00:26:38,060 --> 00:26:39,860
- You swore, Pearl.
- John, don't.

331
00:26:39,980 --> 00:26:41,900
You promised Dad
you wouldn't tell.

332
00:26:42,020 --> 00:26:45,260
I love Mr. Powell
lots and lots, John.

333
00:27:15,060 --> 00:27:16,420
Men.

334
00:27:33,020 --> 00:27:34,860
Fix that window shade.

335
00:27:45,620 --> 00:27:48,300
I was praying.

336
00:27:48,420 --> 00:27:52,540
I'm sorry. I didn't know.
I thought--

337
00:27:52,660 --> 00:27:55,340
You thought, Willa, that
the moment you walked in that door...

338
00:27:55,460 --> 00:27:58,340
I'd start to pawin' you
in that abominable way...

339
00:27:58,420 --> 00:28:01,100
that men are supposed to do
on their weddin' night.

340
00:28:01,180 --> 00:28:02,900
Ain't that right?

341
00:28:05,260 --> 00:28:08,140
I think it's time we made on thing
perf ectly clear, Willa.

342
00:28:08,260 --> 00:28:12,300
Marriage, to me, represents a blending
of two spirits in the sight of heaven.

343
00:28:24,100 --> 00:28:25,500
Get up, Willa.

344
00:28:27,860 --> 00:28:30,620
- Harry, what--
- Get up.

345
00:28:33,300 --> 00:28:36,100
Now go look at yourself
yonder in that mirror.

346
00:28:37,940 --> 00:28:39,780
Do as I say.

347
00:28:52,260 --> 00:28:54,100
Look at yourself.

348
00:28:56,340 --> 00:28:58,860
What do you see, girl?

349
00:28:58,940 --> 00:29:03,780
You see the body of a woman,
a temple of creation and motherhood.

350
00:29:03,860 --> 00:29:07,740
You see the flesh of Eve
that man since Adam has profaned.

351
00:29:07,860 --> 00:29:10,060
That body was meant
for begettin' children.

352
00:29:10,180 --> 00:29:13,260
It was not meant
for the lust of men.

353
00:29:14,900 --> 00:29:17,620
Do you want more children, Willa?

354
00:29:20,020 --> 00:29:23,180
It's the business of this marriage
to mind those two you have now...

355
00:29:23,300 --> 00:29:25,140
not to beget more.

356
00:29:25,220 --> 00:29:26,540
Yes.

357
00:29:34,020 --> 00:29:37,500
All right, you can get in bed now
and stop shiverin'.

358
00:29:39,700 --> 00:29:41,740
Help me to get clean...

359
00:29:41,820 --> 00:29:44,740
so I can be
what Harry wants me to be.

360
00:29:51,940 --> 00:29:54,860
Meanest, orneriest, sneakiest critter
in the whole river, boy.

361
00:29:54,980 --> 00:29:56,300
The gar.

362
00:29:57,780 --> 00:30:00,580
- Here's your can of hooks.
- P'shaw, boy.

363
00:30:00,660 --> 00:30:03,980
Ain't a hook in the land
strong enough to land Mr. Gar.

364
00:30:04,060 --> 00:30:08,140
What a f ellow needs
is a mother wit and a horsehair.

365
00:30:08,260 --> 00:30:10,620
Golly, won't it bust it,
Uncle Birdie?

366
00:30:10,740 --> 00:30:13,820
No, horsehair'll hold
a lumpin' whale.

367
00:30:13,940 --> 00:30:16,300
- You mind my cussin', boy?
- No.

368
00:30:16,380 --> 00:30:20,020
Well, the reason I ask--
Your step-pa bein' a preacher and all.

369
00:30:23,220 --> 00:30:26,660
Never was much of a one
for preachin' myself.

370
00:30:26,740 --> 00:30:28,700
I don't know what's wrong
up at your house...

371
00:30:28,820 --> 00:30:31,300
but always remember, cap...

372
00:30:31,380 --> 00:30:34,660
if you're ever in trouble,
holler and come a-runnin'.

373
00:30:34,740 --> 00:30:36,820
Uncle Birdie's your friend.

374
00:30:41,620 --> 00:30:46,420
There! You slimy, snag-toothed,
bait-stealin' so-and-so!

375
00:30:47,700 --> 00:30:49,380
Amen!

376
00:30:49,460 --> 00:30:51,980
You have all sinned!

377
00:30:52,060 --> 00:30:55,980
Which one of you can say,
as I can say...

378
00:30:56,060 --> 00:30:58,700
that you drove a good man
to murder?

379
00:30:58,820 --> 00:31:00,940
Because I kept a-houndin' him...

380
00:31:01,060 --> 00:31:04,340
for perfume and clothes
and face paint.

381
00:31:04,460 --> 00:31:08,580
And he slew two human beings...

382
00:31:08,660 --> 00:31:11,620
and he come to me and he said...

383
00:31:11,700 --> 00:31:16,460
"Take this money and buy yourself
the clothes and the paint."

384
00:31:17,580 --> 00:31:20,340
But brethren, brethren...

385
00:31:20,460 --> 00:31:23,020
that's where the Lord stepped in.

386
00:31:25,460 --> 00:31:26,540
Yes!

387
00:31:28,340 --> 00:31:31,460
He said, the Lord to that man...

388
00:31:31,540 --> 00:31:36,460
"You take that money
and you throw it in the river."

389
00:31:36,580 --> 00:31:40,220
- In the river!
- In the river!

390
00:32:01,860 --> 00:32:04,500
Now, you're John and you're Pearl.

391
00:32:06,460 --> 00:32:10,700
You'll get awful mad, John.
I done a sin.

392
00:32:10,780 --> 00:32:13,260
I didn't tell no one.

393
00:32:17,540 --> 00:32:19,260
It's all here.

394
00:32:37,300 --> 00:32:40,100
- Oh, yes?
- What are you doing, boy?

395
00:32:40,180 --> 00:32:43,700
- Gettin' Pearl to bed.
- What's takin' you so long about it?

396
00:32:43,820 --> 00:32:45,140
Nothing.

397
00:32:50,580 --> 00:32:53,860
- What's that you're playin' with?
- Pearl's junk.

398
00:32:53,940 --> 00:32:57,060
Mom gets mad when she plays out here
and don't put it away.

399
00:32:57,140 --> 00:32:58,980
Come on, children.

400
00:33:02,540 --> 00:33:04,660
Off to bed with the both of you.

401
00:33:10,820 --> 00:33:12,660
Come here, John.

402
00:33:15,580 --> 00:33:17,980
Your mother tells me
you tattled on me.

403
00:33:18,100 --> 00:33:20,500
She said you told her
I asked where that money was hid.

404
00:33:22,940 --> 00:33:25,260
That wasn't very nice, boy.

405
00:33:25,340 --> 00:33:27,620
- Have a heart.
- Yeah.

406
00:33:29,140 --> 00:33:32,780
Well, it doesn't matter.
It's your word against mine.

407
00:33:32,860 --> 00:33:34,820
It's me your mother believes.

408
00:33:40,060 --> 00:33:42,780
Were you impudent again
to Mr. Powell, John?

409
00:33:42,900 --> 00:33:45,060
Mom, I didn't mean it.

410
00:33:46,220 --> 00:33:48,540
What were you impudent about?

411
00:33:48,660 --> 00:33:51,660
He asked me
about the money again, Mom.

412
00:33:51,740 --> 00:33:56,060
John, you always make up that lie.
There is no money.

413
00:33:56,180 --> 00:33:59,100
Why can't you get that
through your head?

414
00:33:59,220 --> 00:34:01,820
That boy's as stubborn
and as mulish as a sheep.

415
00:34:01,940 --> 00:34:03,940
- It's a shame.
- Good night, Icey.

416
00:34:04,020 --> 00:34:05,980
- Good night, honey.
- Good night, Walt.

417
00:34:06,100 --> 00:34:07,260
Good night, Willa.

418
00:34:09,380 --> 00:34:11,580
Plan on a longer visit next time.

419
00:34:11,700 --> 00:34:14,340
You hardly get settled before
you're frettin' to get home again.

420
00:34:14,420 --> 00:34:16,980
I'm needed to keep peace
and harmony betwixt them.

421
00:34:17,100 --> 00:34:19,820
It's my burden,
and I'm proud of it, Icey.

422
00:34:29,420 --> 00:34:32,780
- Where is the money hid?
- I don't know.

423
00:34:32,900 --> 00:34:35,580
She thinks that money's
at the bottom of the river.

424
00:34:35,700 --> 00:34:38,100
But you and me, we know better,
don't we, little lad?

425
00:34:38,220 --> 00:34:40,140
I don't know nothin'.

426
00:34:40,260 --> 00:34:43,660
Well, never mind, boy.
Summer's young yet.

427
00:34:45,940 --> 00:34:47,260
Come here.

428
00:34:50,500 --> 00:34:52,420
John's a f ellow
that likes to keep secrets.

429
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:54,900
- I'll tell you a secret.
- Yes?

430
00:34:54,980 --> 00:34:57,380
I knowed your daddy.

431
00:34:57,500 --> 00:35:00,340
And do you know
what your daddy told me?

432
00:35:00,460 --> 00:35:02,500
He said,
"You tell my little girl Pearl...

433
00:35:02,580 --> 00:35:05,220
that there's to be no secrets
between her and you."

434
00:35:05,300 --> 00:35:08,700
- Yes.
- All right, now it's your turn.

435
00:35:08,820 --> 00:35:10,620
What secret shall I tell?

436
00:35:10,740 --> 00:35:13,180
Oh, uh, what's your name?

437
00:35:14,860 --> 00:35:17,340
You're just foolin'.
My name's Pearl.

438
00:35:19,300 --> 00:35:23,660
Well, I reckon I'll have to try again.
Where's the money hid?

439
00:35:26,180 --> 00:35:29,460
Pearl, you swore you wouldn't tell!
You swore! You swore!

440
00:35:29,580 --> 00:35:32,180
You hit Daddy with a hairbrush.

441
00:35:34,140 --> 00:35:37,460
Now, you see, we just can't have
anything to do with John.

442
00:35:37,580 --> 00:35:39,860
You and me'll go on down
to the parlor, Pearl.

443
00:35:57,220 --> 00:35:59,940
John is just plumb bad,
through and through.

444
00:36:00,020 --> 00:36:02,980
- John's bad.
- Yes, John's bad.

445
00:36:04,060 --> 00:36:06,460
Tell me another secret
about my dad.

446
00:36:06,580 --> 00:36:08,300
Oh, no. Your turn.

447
00:36:08,420 --> 00:36:11,540
Well, like,
what secret shall I tell?

448
00:36:11,660 --> 00:36:13,940
Where's the money hid?

449
00:36:14,060 --> 00:36:16,900
- John's bad.
- Where's the money hid?

450
00:36:17,020 --> 00:36:20,620
Tell me, you little wretch,
or I'll tear your arm off!

451
00:36:32,580 --> 00:36:35,980
- Icey, I'm worried about Willa.
- How do you mean?

452
00:36:36,060 --> 00:36:38,700
Well, I'm figurin' how to say it
so as you won't get mad.

453
00:36:38,780 --> 00:36:40,700
Say what, Walt Spoon?

454
00:36:40,820 --> 00:36:42,860
- There's somethin' wrong about it.
- About what?

455
00:36:42,940 --> 00:36:45,620
About Mr. Powell.
All of it.

456
00:36:45,740 --> 00:36:47,820
Now, Mother, a body's
got a right to their f eelings.

457
00:36:47,940 --> 00:36:51,060
May the Lord have mercy on you,
Walt Spoon.

458
00:36:51,180 --> 00:36:52,340
Mother, I was just--

459
00:36:56,340 --> 00:36:57,700
Amen.

460
00:36:59,540 --> 00:37:03,820
- Are you through praying?
- I'm through, Harry.

461
00:37:03,900 --> 00:37:06,420
You were listening
outside the parlor window.

462
00:37:06,540 --> 00:37:09,740
- It ain't in the river, is it, Harry?
- Answer me!

463
00:37:09,820 --> 00:37:13,460
Ben never told you
he throwed it in the river, did he?

464
00:37:23,140 --> 00:37:25,260
The children know where it's hid.

465
00:37:25,380 --> 00:37:27,940
John knows.
Is that it, Harry?

466
00:37:32,660 --> 00:37:35,740
Then it's still here
amongst us...

467
00:37:35,860 --> 00:37:38,140
tainting us.

468
00:37:40,660 --> 00:37:43,740
You must've known about it
all along, Harry.

469
00:37:43,860 --> 00:37:47,340
But that ain't the reason
why you married me.

470
00:37:47,460 --> 00:37:49,300
I know that much.

471
00:37:50,900 --> 00:37:54,260
Because the Lord
just wouldn't let it be.

472
00:37:54,380 --> 00:37:57,140
He made you marry me...

473
00:37:57,260 --> 00:38:01,780
so you could show me
the way and the lif e...

474
00:38:01,900 --> 00:38:04,260
and the salvation of my soul.

475
00:38:06,060 --> 00:38:08,420
Ain't that so, Harry.

476
00:38:08,500 --> 00:38:12,140
So you might say that it was the money
that brung us together.

477
00:38:13,820 --> 00:38:15,980
The rest of it don't matter.

478
00:39:11,260 --> 00:39:12,620
Walt, come quick!

479
00:39:12,700 --> 00:39:15,340
- What's wrong, Mother?
- Shhh! He's in there.

480
00:39:15,420 --> 00:39:16,780
- Who?
- Mr. Powell.

481
00:39:16,860 --> 00:39:19,780
Willa has run away.

482
00:39:19,900 --> 00:39:21,300
Just went?

483
00:39:21,420 --> 00:39:23,980
She took off some time in the night
in that old Model-T.

484
00:39:24,100 --> 00:39:26,380
- Oh, is he hit pretty bad?
- All to pieces.

485
00:39:26,460 --> 00:39:28,460
Well, there's a little
peach brandy in here--

486
00:39:28,580 --> 00:39:31,940
- A man of the cloth?
- Well, just a sip.

487
00:39:32,020 --> 00:39:35,140
Walt Spoon,
that's for sickness in the house!

488
00:39:36,340 --> 00:39:37,660
What can we do, Mother?

489
00:39:37,780 --> 00:39:39,740
I thought if you went
and talked to him.

490
00:39:39,860 --> 00:39:42,220
Now, Mother, please.
I'm no good--

491
00:39:45,260 --> 00:39:48,860
- Mr. Powell.
- A strange woman is a narrow pit.

492
00:39:48,980 --> 00:39:52,860
She lieth in wait as for pray and
increaseth the transgressors among men.

493
00:39:54,220 --> 00:39:56,980
My dear, dear friends,
whatever would I do without you?

494
00:39:57,100 --> 00:40:00,100
- Mr. Powell.
- Well, if there's anything--

495
00:40:00,180 --> 00:40:03,660
No, it's my shame, my crown of thorns.
I must wear it bravely.

496
00:40:03,780 --> 00:40:07,100
- What could have possessed that girl?
- Satan.

497
00:40:07,220 --> 00:40:08,780
Didn't you have no inkling?

498
00:40:09,460 --> 00:40:12,060
Yes I did,
from the very first night.

499
00:40:12,180 --> 00:40:14,780
- First night?
- Our honeymoon.

500
00:40:14,900 --> 00:40:16,820
How's that?

501
00:40:16,940 --> 00:40:19,180
She turned me out of the bed.

502
00:40:19,300 --> 00:40:21,380
No!

503
00:40:21,460 --> 00:40:23,660
Well, what do you figure to do?

504
00:40:23,740 --> 00:40:27,620
Do? Why, just stay right here
and take care of them kids.

505
00:40:27,740 --> 00:40:30,860
Maybe it was never meant for a woman
like Willa to taint their young lives.

506
00:40:32,540 --> 00:40:34,380
That's mighty brave of you, preacher.

507
00:40:34,460 --> 00:40:37,940
Oh, I reckon it was just
ordained that way, Brother Spoon.

508
00:40:38,060 --> 00:40:40,540
Didn't she leave no word?

509
00:40:41,540 --> 00:40:45,140
A scrawl, on a notepaper
on the bureau.

510
00:40:45,260 --> 00:40:47,060
I burned it.

511
00:40:47,180 --> 00:40:50,700
Tore it up and burned it,
it stank so strong of hellfire.

512
00:40:50,780 --> 00:40:52,540
Amen!

513
00:40:52,660 --> 00:40:55,660
The pitcher has went to the well
once too often, friends.

514
00:40:55,780 --> 00:40:58,220
Oh, she'll come
draggin' her tail back home.

515
00:40:58,340 --> 00:41:01,980
She'll not be back.
I reckon I'm saf e in promisin' you that.

516
00:41:02,100 --> 00:41:04,220
- Maybe she just run offon a spree.
- Oh, no.

517
00:41:04,340 --> 00:41:07,220
- Well, there's no harm in hoping.
- Ain't no sense in it, neither.

518
00:41:08,860 --> 00:41:11,860
I figured somethin' like that was
brewin' when she went to bed last night.

519
00:41:11,980 --> 00:41:12,980
How?

520
00:41:14,460 --> 00:41:17,180
Well, she tarried around in the kitchen
after I'd gone up.

521
00:41:17,300 --> 00:41:21,260
- When I went to see what was wrong--
- What?

522
00:41:21,380 --> 00:41:24,140
Well, she'd found this jar
of dandelion wine...

523
00:41:24,220 --> 00:41:27,500
that the husband, that Harper,
had hid somewhere in the cellar.

524
00:41:29,020 --> 00:41:30,860
She was drinkin'.

525
00:41:32,180 --> 00:41:35,340
- I tried to save her.
- I know you did, Mr. Powell.

526
00:41:35,460 --> 00:41:37,340
I know how hard you tried.

527
00:41:37,460 --> 00:41:40,140
But the Devil wins sometimes.

528
00:41:40,260 --> 00:41:43,500
Can't nobody say I didn't do
my best to save her.

529
00:42:40,260 --> 00:42:42,460
Leaning

530
00:42:45,140 --> 00:42:50,060
Saf e and secure from all alarm

531
00:42:50,180 --> 00:42:52,540
Leaning

532
00:42:55,060 --> 00:43:00,340
Leaning on the everlasting Arm

533
00:43:02,460 --> 00:43:04,060
Children!

534
00:43:23,540 --> 00:43:24,860
Careful.

535
00:43:26,380 --> 00:43:28,420
Why do we have to hide, John?

536
00:43:31,540 --> 00:43:33,780
- Where's Mom?
- She's gone to Moundsville.

537
00:43:33,900 --> 00:43:36,940
- To see Dad?
- Yes, I reckon that's it.

538
00:43:44,660 --> 00:43:47,500
Now, listen to me, Pearl.
You and me is runnin' off tonight.

539
00:43:47,580 --> 00:43:48,780
Why?

540
00:43:48,860 --> 00:43:52,140
If we stay here,
somethin' awful will happen to us.

541
00:43:52,220 --> 00:43:55,340
- Won't Daddy Powell take care of us?
- No.

542
00:43:55,420 --> 00:43:58,060
That's just it. No.

543
00:44:05,140 --> 00:44:07,820
- Where are we going, John?
- Somewhere. I don't know yet.

544
00:44:09,260 --> 00:44:12,180
- I'm hungry, John.
- We'll steal something to eat.

545
00:44:12,300 --> 00:44:14,460
It'll spoil our supper.

546
00:44:19,940 --> 00:44:22,780
I can hear you whisperin', children,
so I know you're down there.

547
00:44:22,900 --> 00:44:25,700
I can f eel myself gettin' awful mad.

548
00:44:29,180 --> 00:44:32,940
I'm out of patience, children.
I'm coming to find you now.

549
00:44:33,060 --> 00:44:36,620
Yoo-hoo! Mr. Powell!

550
00:44:40,820 --> 00:44:45,340
- Well, well, Mrs. Spoon.
- Where are the children?

551
00:44:45,460 --> 00:44:47,500
They're down there
in that cellar playin' games.

552
00:44:47,620 --> 00:44:51,420
They won't mind me when I call them.
I'm at my wit's end, Mrs. Spoon.

553
00:45:01,580 --> 00:45:03,460
Shake a leg!

554
00:45:09,020 --> 00:45:11,460
Well, well, well. What's that?

555
00:45:11,580 --> 00:45:14,900
Just a little hot supper
I fixed for you and the children.

556
00:45:15,020 --> 00:45:17,500
It seemed the least we could do.

557
00:45:18,900 --> 00:45:21,540
I won't have you worryin'
poor Mr. Powell another minute.

558
00:45:21,620 --> 00:45:24,580
Just look at you.
Dust and filth from top to toe.

559
00:45:24,660 --> 00:45:27,180
Want me to take 'em up
and wash 'em good?

560
00:45:27,260 --> 00:45:31,380
No, thank you, dear Icey.
Thank you. I'll tend to them.

561
00:45:31,500 --> 00:45:35,780
Don't be too hard on them, preacher.
Poor, motherless children.

562
00:45:35,900 --> 00:45:39,820
Remember now, Mr. Powell,
don't be afraid to call on us.

563
00:45:46,180 --> 00:45:48,940
Good-bye, Mrs. Spoon,
and thanks again.

564
00:45:56,580 --> 00:46:00,260
Now, weren't you afraid, little lambs,
down there in all that dark?

565
00:46:16,300 --> 00:46:18,580
They'll think it was me.

566
00:46:18,700 --> 00:46:21,740
They'll think it was
poor old Uncle Birdie.

567
00:46:24,500 --> 00:46:27,180
Oh, if you could've seen her, Bess.

568
00:46:28,340 --> 00:46:30,460
Down there in the deep place...

569
00:46:31,380 --> 00:46:33,900
with her hair wavin' soft and lazy...

570
00:46:34,020 --> 00:46:37,300
like meadow grass under floodwater.

571
00:46:38,580 --> 00:46:40,900
And that slit in her throat...

572
00:46:40,980 --> 00:46:43,500
like she had an extra mouth.

573
00:46:47,340 --> 00:46:50,900
You're the only human mortal
I can go to, Bess.

574
00:46:52,060 --> 00:46:56,180
If I go to the law,
they'll hang it on me.

575
00:47:02,220 --> 00:47:05,260
Sweet heaven,
save poor old Uncle Birdie.

576
00:47:11,220 --> 00:47:13,780
- I'm hungry.
- Sure.

577
00:47:13,900 --> 00:47:18,780
And there's fried chicken, sweet
potatoes, corn bread and apple cobbler.

578
00:47:19,940 --> 00:47:22,620
- Can I have my supper, please?
- Naturally.

579
00:47:22,740 --> 00:47:25,060
- Can I have milk too?
- Mm-hmm.

580
00:47:25,140 --> 00:47:28,380
But first we'll have a little talk
about our secrets.

581
00:47:28,500 --> 00:47:30,740
- No.
- And why not, pray tell?

582
00:47:30,860 --> 00:47:34,860
- 'Cause John said I mustn't.
- Never mind what John said!

583
00:47:34,940 --> 00:47:36,980
John's a meddler.

584
00:47:37,100 --> 00:47:39,340
Now, stop that snivelin'.

585
00:47:39,420 --> 00:47:42,300
Here. Do you know what that is?

586
00:47:42,420 --> 00:47:45,500
Want to see something cute?
Now look.

587
00:47:46,580 --> 00:47:49,180
How about that?

588
00:47:49,300 --> 00:47:51,940
This is what I use on meddlers.

589
00:47:52,020 --> 00:47:54,140
John might be a meddler.

590
00:47:54,260 --> 00:47:57,300
No! No, little lamb,
don't touch it.

591
00:47:57,420 --> 00:47:59,580
Don't touch my knif e.
That makes me mad.

592
00:47:59,700 --> 00:48:02,380
It makes me very, very mad.

593
00:48:02,460 --> 00:48:05,340
Now just tell me,
where's the money hid?

594
00:48:05,460 --> 00:48:07,820
But I swore, I promised John
I wouldn't tell.

595
00:48:07,900 --> 00:48:10,620
John doesn't matter!

596
00:48:10,740 --> 00:48:15,540
Can't I get that through your head,
you poor, silly disgusting wretch?

597
00:48:20,820 --> 00:48:23,340
There, now, you made me
lose my temper.

598
00:48:24,940 --> 00:48:27,380
I'm sorry. I'm real sorry.

599
00:48:28,660 --> 00:48:31,620
Just tell me, where's it hid, honey?

600
00:48:31,700 --> 00:48:34,100
- I'll tell.
- I told you to keep your mouth shut.

601
00:48:34,220 --> 00:48:36,780
It ain't fair to make Pearl tell
when she swore she wouldn't.

602
00:48:36,860 --> 00:48:39,860
- I'll tell.
- Well, I declare.

603
00:48:39,980 --> 00:48:43,700
Sometimes I think poor old John
might make it to heaven yet.

604
00:48:43,820 --> 00:48:45,260
All right, boy,
where's the money?

605
00:48:45,380 --> 00:48:49,260
In the cellar, buried
under a stone in the floor.

606
00:48:49,380 --> 00:48:51,340
It'll go hard if I find
you're lying, boy.

607
00:48:51,460 --> 00:48:53,780
I'm not lying.
Go look for yourself.

608
00:48:56,100 --> 00:48:57,420
All right.

609
00:49:07,460 --> 00:49:10,620
- Come along.
- What?

610
00:49:12,660 --> 00:49:15,740
Go ahead of me, the both of you.

611
00:49:15,860 --> 00:49:18,380
Down those stairs.

612
00:49:21,620 --> 00:49:23,980
You don't reckon I'd leave here,
do you, boy?

613
00:49:24,100 --> 00:49:28,060
- Don't you believe me?
- Why, sure, boy. Sure.

614
00:49:31,100 --> 00:49:32,180
Where, now?

615
00:49:32,300 --> 00:49:36,220
Mind, no tricks, now.
I can't abide a liar.

616
00:49:36,340 --> 00:49:37,740
Yonder.

617
00:49:41,020 --> 00:49:42,420
Oh, no, you don't.

618
00:49:47,580 --> 00:49:49,060
Now, where, boy? Where?

619
00:49:49,140 --> 00:49:51,700
Under the stone on the floor.

620
00:50:00,500 --> 00:50:03,540
- This is concrete!
- John made a sin.

621
00:50:03,660 --> 00:50:05,460
John told a lie.

622
00:50:08,180 --> 00:50:10,540
The Lord's a-talkin' to me now.

623
00:50:10,660 --> 00:50:12,260
He's a-sayin'...

624
00:50:12,340 --> 00:50:15,660
"A liar is an abomination
before Mine eyes."

625
00:50:17,420 --> 00:50:18,820
Speak, boy.
Where's it hid?

626
00:50:20,020 --> 00:50:21,780
Speak!

627
00:50:21,900 --> 00:50:23,820
Speak, or I'll cut your throat
and leave you to drip...

628
00:50:23,940 --> 00:50:26,100
like a hog hung up
in butcherin' time.

629
00:50:26,220 --> 00:50:29,380
Pearl, Shut up!
Pearl, You swore!

630
00:50:30,700 --> 00:50:32,380
You could save him, little bird.

631
00:50:32,500 --> 00:50:35,340
It's on my doll!

632
00:50:38,220 --> 00:50:40,020
The doll!

633
00:50:43,020 --> 00:50:45,100
Why, sure.

634
00:50:45,220 --> 00:50:47,420
Last place anybody'd think to look.

635
00:51:13,980 --> 00:51:15,380
Uncle Birdie Steptoe.

636
00:51:16,540 --> 00:51:20,420
Open that door, you spawn
of the devil's own strumpet!

637
00:51:46,820 --> 00:51:48,660
Uncle Birdie!

638
00:51:53,460 --> 00:51:56,140
Hide us, Uncle Birdie!
He's a-comin' with his knif e!

639
00:51:59,060 --> 00:52:03,060
It's me. John Harper and Pearl.
You told me to come.

640
00:52:03,180 --> 00:52:04,700
Oh, please!

641
00:52:04,820 --> 00:52:06,620
Please wake up!

642
00:52:06,740 --> 00:52:09,780
I swear on the Book,
I never done it.

643
00:52:09,900 --> 00:52:11,700
I never--

644
00:52:24,860 --> 00:52:26,860
There's still the river.

645
00:52:34,580 --> 00:52:36,540
The skiff is under the willows.

646
00:52:54,540 --> 00:52:55,580
Children!

647
00:54:33,620 --> 00:54:35,900
Once upon a time

648
00:54:36,020 --> 00:54:39,180
There was a pretty fly

649
00:54:39,260 --> 00:54:41,900
He had a pretty wif e

650
00:54:41,980 --> 00:54:44,300
This pretty fly

651
00:54:45,180 --> 00:54:50,340
But one day she flew away

652
00:54:50,420 --> 00:54:54,260
Flew away

653
00:54:54,380 --> 00:54:57,220
She had two pretty

654
00:54:57,340 --> 00:54:59,980
Children

655
00:55:00,060 --> 00:55:02,100
But one night

656
00:55:02,220 --> 00:55:06,940
These two pretty children

657
00:55:07,020 --> 00:55:09,860
Flew away

658
00:55:13,300 --> 00:55:16,900
Into the sky

659
00:55:16,980 --> 00:55:22,580
Into the moon

660
00:55:37,380 --> 00:55:40,300
"Dear Walt and Icey,
I bet you've been worried...

661
00:55:40,420 --> 00:55:42,540
and gave us up for lost.

662
00:55:42,620 --> 00:55:44,620
Took the kids down here with me
for a visit...

663
00:55:44,740 --> 00:55:47,820
to my sister Elsie's farm.

664
00:55:47,900 --> 00:55:50,820
Thought a little change of scenery
would do us all a world of good...

665
00:55:50,900 --> 00:55:53,860
after so much trouble and heartache.

666
00:55:53,940 --> 00:55:57,620
At least the kids will get
a-plenty of good home cookin'.

667
00:55:57,740 --> 00:55:59,740
Your devoted Harry Powell."

668
00:55:59,820 --> 00:56:01,860
Now, ain't you relieved, Walt?

669
00:56:01,940 --> 00:56:04,100
Sure. But you was worried too, Mother.

670
00:56:04,180 --> 00:56:06,820
Takin' off with never a word
of good-bye.

671
00:56:06,900 --> 00:56:10,180
I got to figurin' maybe them gypsies
busted in and done off with all of them.

672
00:56:10,260 --> 00:56:12,660
You and your gypsies.
They've been gone a week.

673
00:56:12,780 --> 00:56:16,580
Sure. But not before one of them knif ed
a farmer and stole his horse.

674
00:56:16,700 --> 00:56:19,100
Never caught the gypsy,
nor the horse.

675
00:56:34,940 --> 00:56:37,900
Such times
when young 'uns run the roads.

676
00:56:38,020 --> 00:56:39,860
Go away, children.

677
00:56:46,580 --> 00:56:50,820
Hungry, I suppose. Well, I can't
spare you more than one potato apiece.

678
00:56:52,020 --> 00:56:54,500
- Where are your folks?
- I ain't got none.

679
00:56:54,580 --> 00:56:56,980
Oh, go away. Go away.

680
00:57:05,540 --> 00:57:08,780
An ungrateful child is an abomination
before the eyes of God.

681
00:57:08,860 --> 00:57:10,700
The world is fast
going to damnation...

682
00:57:10,780 --> 00:57:13,220
because of impudent young 'uns
flyin' in the face of age.

683
00:57:27,100 --> 00:57:29,220
I make soup out of them...

684
00:57:29,300 --> 00:57:31,820
but I wouldn't know how
to go about getting him open.

685
00:58:27,020 --> 00:58:29,260
We're gonna spend the night on land.

